he history of the book in China is a topic that has been little explored. This pioneering volume of essays, written by historians, art historians, and literary scholars, introduces the major issues in the social and cultural history of the book in late imperial China. Informed by many insights from the rich literature on the history of the Western book, these essays investigate the relationship between the manuscript and print culture; the emergence of urban and rural publishing centers; the expanding audience for books; the development of niche markets and specialized publishing of fiction, drama, non-Han texts, and genealogies; and more.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBookszChinaxHistory. 0aPublishers and publishingzChinaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aasian.  abooks.  achinese drama.  achinese fiction.  achinese history.  achinese literature.  achinese society.  achinese students.  acultural history.  agenealogies.  ahistory of the book.  aimperial china.  alanguage.  aliteracy scripts.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary theory.  aliterature.  amanuscript.  aming dynasty.  ananjing.  anon han texts.  anonfiction.  aprint culture.  aprinting.  apublishing.  aqianlong.  aqing dynasty.  areading audience.  areading traditions.  arural publishing.  asanshan street.  aspecialized publishing.  athree mountains street.  aurban china.  awomen readers.1 aBrokaw, Cynthia J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrokaw, Cynthia J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBurkus-Chasson, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlitz, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChia, Lucille, econtributor.4ctb4